exible than ever.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>For example, let&#8217;s say you always find yourself adding the same two blocks to your posts. Perhaps it&#8217;s two side-by-side buttons. If you&#8217;ve done this before, then you know what it takes to make this happen:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Add a Columns block with two columns</li>\r\n<li>Next, add a Button block to the left column</li>\r\n<li>Then. add a Button block to the right column</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>What a pain. Three blocks to create what essentially amounts to one.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img class=\"wp-image-2207749\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2.jpg\" alt=\"Showing an outline with two columns each with a rounded blue button that says Button as the label.\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2.jpg 831w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-300x128.jpg 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-665x284.jpg 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-140x60.jpg 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-768x328.jpg 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-430x184.jpg 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-645x276.jpg 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-460x197.jpg 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-512x219.jpg 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-707x302.jpg 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-600x256.jpg 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons-2-500x214.jpg 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 831px) 100vw, 831px\" /></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>That&#8217;s what block patterns are designed to fix.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of dropping in multiple blocks to create one element, block patterns allow you to combine blocks into a single group that can be reused whenever you want. WordPress even provides several of these block patterns right out of the box.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img class=\"wp-image-2207730\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu.png\" alt=\"The block menu opened as a sidebar to the left of the content editor with the Patterns tab active. There\'s a gray search box above the patterns menu. Below the menu are previews of the first couple of patterns, including two buttons, three buttons, and columns.\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu.png 2354w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-300x246.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-665x545.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-104x85.png 104w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-768x630.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-1536x1259.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-2048x1679.png 2048w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-430x353.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-645x529.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-2000x1640.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-1068x876.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-460x377.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-1602x1313.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-1074x881.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-512x420.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-1611x1321.png 1611w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-1344x1102.png 1344w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-646x530.png 646w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-2016x1653.png 2016w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-600x492.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-menu-500x410.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2354px) 100vw, 2354px\" /></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Taking our button example, we can group the pieces together and save them as one block for later use. But before we get there, let&#8217;s draw another important distinction.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Block patterns are super similar to reusable blocks.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The block editor already <em>sort of</em> allows us to accomplish what block patterns do with <strong>reusable blocks</strong>: Drop some blocks into the editor as a group, click the little menu icon, then select the &#8220;Add to Reusable Blocks&#8221; option.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img class=\"wp-image-2207705\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-665x353.png\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-665x353.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-300x159.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-140x74.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-768x407.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-430x228.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-645x342.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-1068x567.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-460x244.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-1074x570.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-512x272.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-707x375.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-600x318.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block-500x265.png 500w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-reusable-block.png 1376w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 665px) 100vw, 665px\" /></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Cool! Now give it a name and we can use it anytime we need two buttons right next to each other.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-video\"><video src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-inline-buttons.mp4\" autoplay=\"autoplay\" loop=\"loop\" muted=\"\" controls=\"controls\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\"></video></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>So, why use block patterns when reusable blocks can also save groups of blocks?</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>One reason is because when you make a change to a reusable block, those changes will automatically apply anywhere the block is used, whether it&#8217;s on the same post, or another one. It is possible to convert a reusable block to a regular block so that the changes only apply to that one instance, but that can break the layout of the grouped blocks and requires you to modify a bunch of content.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Block patterns, on the other hand, are editable right out of the gate. They simply provide a layout of blocks where you can create and customize your content.</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/wordpress/block-patterns-to-use-with-the-events-calendar/\"><em><strong>Related: Check out these block patterns to use with The Events Calendar.</strong></em></a></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>How to register a block pattern</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>WordPress introduced a new <code><a href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/developers/block-api/block-patterns/#register_block_pattern\">register_block_pattern()</a></code> function that  true to its name  registers a block pattern so you can use it in the future. All the documentation for it is available on WordPress.org, so we won&#8217;t detail everything here. What&#8217;s important to know are the arguments it takes. These are the two required arguments:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong><code>title</code>:</strong> The pattern name you&#8217;ll see in the Pattern menu.</li>\r\n<li><strong><code>content</code>:</strong> The pattern code.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>There are a few others:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong><code>description</code>:</strong> A short blurb that describes the pattern.</li>\r\n<li><strong><code>categories</code>:</strong> Groups the pattern with other patterns in the same categories.</li>\r\n<li><strong><code>keywords</code>:</strong> Tells WordPress if searching certain words in the block menu should return the pattern as a search result. This is super handy for making a pattern more discoverable. For example, a pattern that contains a row of three cards called &#8220;Cards&#8221; can be found when searching for &#8220;Three&#8221; or any other combination of words.</li>\r\n<li><strong><code>viewportWidth</code>:</strong> This gives you a little extra control over how the pattern looks in the block inserter, like making it a full-width item.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>To start, let&#8217;s define a pattern category.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>This is totally optional and only really necessary if you want to register a pattern under an entirely new category. The patterns that are already available in WordPress include several existing categories:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Buttons</li>\r\n<li>Columns</li>\r\n<li>Gallery</li>\r\n<li>Headers</li>\r\n<li>Text</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>If you can use any of those, great! If not, create one! Either way, if you don&#8217;t want to categorize a pattern, it will automatically go into an &#8220;Uncategorized&#8221; category the same way uncategorized posts do.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The <code><a href=\"https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/developers/block-api/block-patterns/#register_block_pattern_category\">register_block_pattern_category()</a></code> is what we need to create a new category. Let&#8217;s register one called &#8220;Events&#8221;:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>register_block_pattern_category(\r\n  \'events\',\r\n  array( \'label\' =&gt; __( \'Events\', \'my-block-patterns\' ) )\r\n);</code></pre>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>As you can see, all it really takes is a single <code>label</code> argument. The part with <code>my-block-patterns</code> is just the namespace of your plugin or theme&#8230; wherever you&#8217;re registering block patterns.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Next, create the pattern in WordPress.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Now, we could write the code for a pattern directly in the <code>register_block_pattern()</code> function. But that would be a test of patience. It&#8217;s much easier to sketch the pattern in the block editor and then copy the code to the function.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>First, create a group. Then, drop some blocks in that group. Next, select the group, open the block options menu, and select &#8220;Copy&#8221; option.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img class=\"wp-image-2207738\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2.png\" alt=\"Showing a selected group containing two black buttons with the options menu expanded over the group content with the copy option selected.\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2.png 1200w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-300x246.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-665x544.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-104x85.png 104w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-768x628.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-430x352.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-645x528.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-1068x874.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-460x376.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-1074x879.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-512x419.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-648x530.png 648w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-600x491.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-group-copy-2-500x409.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" /></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Copying a block copies the HTML and markup for the block. That&#8217;s what we need for the <code>content</code> argument our register function.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>But first&#8230;</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>We need to escape the copied code.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>That&#8217;s right. We aren&#8217;t able to simply paste it in as is. Fortunately, <a href=\"https://codebeautify.org/json-escape-unescape\">there&#8217;s an online tool</a> that will escape the code for us. Paste it there, clock the &#8220;Escape&#8221; button, and then copy the code it outputs.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img class=\"wp-image-2207741\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code.png\" alt=\"Showing the online tool for escaping code. There is a texture for pasting the code that needs to be escaped above another one containing the generated code.\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code.png 2420w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-300x223.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-665x495.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-114x85.png 114w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-768x572.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-1536x1144.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-2048x1525.png 2048w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-260x195.png 260w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-430x320.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-645x480.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-2000x1489.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-1068x795.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-460x343.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-1602x1193.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-1074x800.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-512x381.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-1611x1200.png 1611w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-1480x1102.png 1480w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-707x526.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-600x447.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-escape-code-500x372.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2420px) 100vw, 2420px\" /></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Hold on to this for now. We&#8217;ll need it in just a bit.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Register the pattern.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>We have some code for a pattern. We have a function to register a pattern. Now, let&#8217;s put them together to create a pattern.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Here&#8217;s our pattern complete with the markup we escaped a moment ago. We&#8217;re hooking into the register function and calling it on <code>init</code>:</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>function tec_register_block_patterns() {\r\n\r\n  // Let\'s check if block patterns are even supported\r\n  if ( class_exists( \'WP_Block_Patterns_Registry\' ) ) {\r\n    \r\n    // Start the pattern\r\n    register_block_pattern(\r\n      // The registered name of the pattern\r\n      \'tec/two-buttons\',\r\n      array(\r\n        // The pattern name (required)\r\n        \'title\'       =&gt; __( \'Two Buttons\', \'textdomain\' ),\r\n        // The pattern description (optional)\r\n        \'description\' =&gt; _x( \'Displays two buttons on the same line.\', \'Block pattern description\', \'textdomain\' ),\r\n        // The escaped pattern code (required)\r\n        \'content\'     =&gt; \"&lt;!-- wp:group --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-group\\\"&gt;&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-group__inner-container\\\"&gt;&lt;!-- wp:columns --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-columns\\\"&gt;&lt;!-- wp:column --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-column\\\"&gt;&lt;!-- wp:buttons --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-buttons\\\"&gt;&lt;!-- wp:button --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-button\\\"&gt;&lt;a class=\\\"wp-block-button__link\\\"&gt;Button&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:button --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:buttons --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:column --&gt;\\n\\n&lt;!-- wp:column --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-column\\\"&gt;&lt;!-- wp:buttons --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-buttons\\\"&gt;&lt;!-- wp:button --&gt;\\n&lt;div class=\\\"wp-block-button\\\"&gt;&lt;a class=\\\"wp-block-button__link\\\"&gt;Button&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:button --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:buttons --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:column --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:columns --&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\\n&lt;!-- /wp:group --&gt;\",\r\n        // Pattern categories (optional)\r\n        \'categories\'  =&gt; array( \'events\' ),\r\n      )\r\n    );\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n\r\n// Register the pattern on init\r\nadd_action( \'init\', \'tec_register_block_patterns\' );</code></pre>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Start using the pattern!</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Now we can head back to the editor. Open up the block inserter, search for the pattern, and select it from the results.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full\"><img class=\"wp-image-2207747\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview.png\" alt=\"Showing the Two Buttons example pattern in the block inserter which is open to the left of the post content.\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview.png 2716w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-300x216.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-665x478.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-118x85.png 118w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-768x552.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-1536x1104.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-2048x1472.png 2048w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-430x309.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-645x464.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-2000x1437.png 2000w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-1068x768.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-460x331.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-1602x1151.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-1074x772.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-512x368.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-1611x1158.png 1611w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-1533x1102.png 1533w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-707x508.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-600x431.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/block-patterns-preview-500x359.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2716px) 100vw, 2716px\" /></figure>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>Start using block patterns with The Events Calendar.</h2>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>This post isn&#8217;t complete if we didn&#8217;t have <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/wordpress/block-patterns-to-use-with-the-events-calendar/\">a few patterns to take with you</a>. So, we created a little extension you can install to add some patterns to use with The Events Calendar.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"wp-block-buttons\">\r\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link has-background\" style=\"background-color: #313df5;\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/extensions/event-block-patterns/\">Get Extension</a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/wordpress/how-to-work-with-wordpress-block-patterns/\">How to Work With WordPress Block Patterns</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"Virtual Events 1.1.1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:80:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/virtual-events/virtual-events-1-1-1/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 22 Oct 2020 19:42:45 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:14:\"Virtual Events\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2209895\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:611:\"<p>Summary Maintenance Release Virtual Events 1.1.1 features a quick update to prevent an infinite loop on single events when using object caching (props @therealgilles). This previously caused a conflict with the Redis Cache plugin. This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/virtual-events/virtual-events-1-1-1/\">Virtual Events 1.1.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1698:\"\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Maintenance Release</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p style=\"font-size:18px\">Virtual Events 1.1.1 features a quick update to prevent an infinite loop on single events when using object caching (props @therealgilles). This previously caused a conflict with the Redis Cache plugin.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always a good idea to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>&nbsp;your site and test changes in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>&nbsp;before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Translations</h4>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">20 strings updated, 6 fuzzied, and 7 obsoleted</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/virtual-events/virtual-events-1-1-1/\">Virtual Events 1.1.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:60:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16:\"Filter Bar 5.0.1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:61:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/filter-bar-5-0-1/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 22 Oct 2020 14:27:36 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"Filter Bar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2209643\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:600:\"<p>Summary Maintenance Release Filter Bar 5.0.1. resolves an issue that prevented the events page from scrolling properly, as well as an issue where the [tribe_events] shortcode pagination triggered a notice. This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always a good idea to&#160;backup&#160;your&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/filter-bar-5-0-1/\">Filter Bar 5.0.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2587:\"\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Maintenance Release</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">Filter Bar 5.0.1. resolves an issue that prevented the events page from scrolling properly, as well as an issue where the <code>[tribe_events]</code> shortcode pagination triggered a notice.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always a good idea to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>&nbsp;your site and test changes in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>&nbsp;before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/2705.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Fixed</h4>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">Bugs that were squashed in this release:</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>We prevent the events page from scrolling down to open dropdown and multi-select filters after a filter has been selected.</li><li>We also prevent <code>[tribe_events]</code> shortcode pagination from triggering a notice on the filter-button due to a missing parameter.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\"></div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\"></div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Translations</h4>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">32 strings have been updated with this release.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/filter-bar-5-0-1/\">Filter Bar 5.0.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"Events Calendar Pro 5.1.6\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/events-calendar-pro/events-calendar-pro-5-1-6/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 22 Oct 2020 14:26:06 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"Events Calendar Pro\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2209637\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:625:\"<p>Summary Maintenance Release Events Calendar Pro 5.1.6 features the correct countdown widget so that it shows the absolute time until event, regardless of the timezone. This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always a good idea to&#160;backup&#160;your site and test changes in&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/events-calendar-pro/events-calendar-pro-5-1-6/\">Events Calendar Pro 5.1.6</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1623:\"\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Maintenance Release</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">Events Calendar Pro 5.1.6 features the correct countdown widget so that it shows the absolute time until event, regardless of the timezone.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always a good idea to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>&nbsp;your site and test changes in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>&nbsp;before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Translations</h4>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p>1 string has been updated in this release.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/events-calendar-pro/events-calendar-pro-5-1-6/\">Events Calendar Pro 5.1.6</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:25:\"The Events Calendar 5.2.1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:90:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/the-events-calendar/the-events-calendar-5-2-1/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 22 Oct 2020 14:24:12 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"The Events Calendar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2209613\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:591:\"<p>Summary Maintenance Release The Events Calendar 5.2.1 features an update to the REST API that allows our users to more easily update events that way with the updated calendar views, as well as a fix for the shortcode category view that now paginates correctly. This is a minor release with no template updates, so it&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/the-events-calendar/the-events-calendar-5-2-1/\">The Events Calendar 5.2.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Jaime Marchwinski\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3792:\"\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Maintenance Release</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">The Events Calendar 5.2.1 features an update to the REST API that allows our users to more easily update events that way with the updated calendar views, as well as a fix for the shortcode category view that now paginates correctly.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This is a minor release with no template updates, so it should be smooth sailing when updating. That said, its always a good idea to&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-site-backups/\">backup</a>&nbsp;your site and test changes in a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/creating-and-using-a-wordpress-staging-site/\">development environment</a>&nbsp;before installing this on your live site, as you would with any other WordPress update.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\"></div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\"></div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/2705.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Fixed</h4>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p>Bugs that were squashed in this release:</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>We have changed the AJAX request method from GET to POST to avoid issues with too long URLs, which improves the ability to use the REST API with the updated calendar views.</li><li>We added the <code>tribe_events_views_v2_endpoint_method</code> filter to allow controlling the HTTP method that users should use to fetch their content from the back-end endpoint.</li><li>We added the <code>tribe_events_views_v2_endpoint_url</code> filter to allow controlling the URL that users should use to fetch their content from the back-end endpoint.</li><li>We now prevent the Event Aggregator 15 minute Cron Schedule from being created when not required (props @jetxpert).</li><li>We added a filter to toggle off the <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/k/using-the-template-management-filters/\">event templates hijack</a>, which will improve theme builder compatibility for our users.</li><li>We have resolved an issue so that the correct URL is used when exporting events in the calendar&#8217;s month view.</li><li>We now avoid loading the same CSS file twice on the back-end, which previously affected the Add Event page for Community Events users.</li><li>We now ensure that the <code>[tribe_events]</code> shortcode Previous and Next URLs handle categories gracefully.</li><li>We updated our use of Monolog logger to avoid issues when the plugins are used together with the WooCommerce Bookings plugin.</li></ul>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Translations</h4>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">3 strings were added and 200 strings have been updated.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/the-events-calendar/the-events-calendar-5-2-1/\">The Events Calendar 5.2.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:46:\"Do I Need Event Tickets or Event Tickets Plus?\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:86:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/do-i-need-event-tickets-or-event-tickets-plus/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 22 Oct 2020 14:21:54 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10:\"What\'s New\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2209478\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:587:\"<p>If you use your WordPress site to manage events, chances are you also need a way to sell tickets or collect RSVPs. Luckily, its easy to set up your site to sell tickets and handle registration by using our free Event Tickets plugin or the premium Event Tickets Plus. But how do you know which&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/do-i-need-event-tickets-or-event-tickets-plus/\">Do I Need Event Tickets or Event Tickets Plus?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Lauren\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:16666:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you use your WordPress site to manage events, chances are you also need a way to sell tickets or collect RSVPs.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Luckily, its easy to set up your site to sell tickets and handle registration by using our </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-event-tickets/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">free Event Tickets plugin or the premium Event Tickets Plus</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. But how do you know which tool is right for you? Should you go with Plus, or will the free plugin provide everything you need?</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The answer depends on your ticketing preferences and objectives. Here are a few pointers to help you decide between Event Tickets and Event Tickets Plus.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need a ticketing solution that doesnt charge fees? Go with Event Tickets </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">or </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The beauty of selling event tickets on your own website with our plugins is that you cut out the middleman: No third-party vendors, which means nobody takes a cut of your ticket sales. If youre looking for an alternative to Eventbrite or Facebook Events, this provides a great way to </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/tips/sell-tickets-for-events-on-your-own-website/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">own your events and increase your margins</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Whether you use Event Tickets or Event Tickets Plus, you keep 100 percent of your revenue. We dont take a single penny.</span></p>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2209927\" style=\"width: 1258px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2209927\" class=\"wp-image-2209927 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1248\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees.png 1248w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-300x240.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-665x533.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-106x85.png 106w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-768x615.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-430x345.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-645x517.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-1068x856.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-460x369.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-1074x861.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-512x410.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-661x530.png 661w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-600x481.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-manage-events-avoid-fees-500x401.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1248px) 100vw, 1248px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2209927\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Manage events on your own website and avoid fees.</p></div></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need a ticketing platform that works with or without a calendar? Go with Event Tickets </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">or </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Thats rightyou dont even need a </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-events-calendar/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">calendar on your website</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to sell tickets for your events. With Event Tickets and Event Tickets Plus, you can attach ticket sales to any page or post on your WordPress site.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">That said, our ticketing plugins are part of The Events Calendar family, which means theyre designed to work seamlessly with the rest of our plugins that power </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-events-calendar/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">calendars</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/promoter/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">email marketing</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-virtual-events/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">virtual events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, and more.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need a powerful ticketing tool without extra bells and whistles? Go with Event Tickets.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our free Event Tickets plugin has everything you need to get started in minutes.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">All the basics are included: You get ticket sales, RSVPs, and email confirmations. The free plugin also comes with custom ticket tiers to differentiate between ticket types, a ticket stock countdown, an optional public attendees list, and powerful reporting so you can generate sales and attendee reports.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need custom registration fields? Go with Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If youre looking for the flexibility to create your own custom registration fields, Event Tickets Plus has you covered. You can collect all the information you need during registration, from T-shirt sizes to meal preferences (or anything else you need to know). With the free Event Tickets plugin, youre limited to basic registration fields, like name and email address.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need an easy, professional check-in solution during events? Go with Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With Event Tickets Plus, you have access to a </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-use-qr-ticket-check-in-on-the-event-tickets-plus-mobile-app/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">mobile check-in app</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> that lets you scan ticket QR codes at the door. You can scan paper tickets or tickets from attendees mobile devicesno big deal if someone forgets to print tickets in advance. The mobile app works on both iOS and Android.</span></p>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2209925\" style=\"width: 1258px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2209925\" class=\"wp-image-2209925 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1248\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner.png 1248w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-300x240.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-665x533.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-106x85.png 106w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-768x615.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-430x345.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-645x517.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-1068x856.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-460x369.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-1074x861.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-512x410.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-661x530.png 661w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-600x481.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-scanner-500x401.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1248px) 100vw, 1248px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2209925\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Scan tickets with the handy Event Tickets Plus mobile app.</p></div></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need advanced ticket inventory options? Go with Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With Event Tickets Plus, each ticket has its own price, stock, and SKU, which makes it easy to manage your inventory.</span></p>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2209922\" style=\"width: 1258px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2209922\" class=\"wp-image-2209922 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1248\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory.png 1248w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-300x240.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-665x533.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-106x85.png 106w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-768x615.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-430x345.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-645x517.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-1068x856.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-460x369.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-1074x861.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-512x410.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-661x530.png 661w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-600x481.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-advanced-ticket-inventory-500x401.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1248px) 100vw, 1248px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2209922\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Use advanced features to keep track of your ticket inventory.</p></div></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need to embed the same tickets or RSVPs across multiple pages? Go with Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Once youve created a ticket for an event, you can use </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/introducing-new-shortcodes-for-event-tickets-plus/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">shortcodes</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to add them to any page or post on your site using Event Tickets Plus.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When might you need this feature? Lets say you created a landing page to promote an event and you want to drop the tickets on that page. Shortcodes make this easy.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another super-handy shortcode is the protected content shortcode, which lets you embed content thats only visible after a user has purchased a ticket or submitted their RSVP.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need extra support for online events? Go with Event Tickets Plus (combined with </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-virtual-events/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Virtual Events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">).</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Its easy to monetize your virtual events by combining the power of Event Tickets Plus with our </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-virtual-events/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Virtual Events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> add-on. By using these plugins together, you get advanced Zoom integration and the option to email an event link after purchase, so that only registered attendees have access to the link or livestream.</span></p>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2209926\" style=\"width: 1258px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2209926\" class=\"wp-image-2209926 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1248\" height=\"1000\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events.png 1248w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-300x240.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-665x533.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-106x85.png 106w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-768x615.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-430x345.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-645x517.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-1068x856.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-460x369.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-1074x861.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-512x410.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-661x530.png 661w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-600x481.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/blog-et-or-plus-event-tickets-with-virtual-events-500x401.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1248px) 100vw, 1248px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2209926\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Use Event Tickets Plus alongside Virtual Events to optimize your ticketing and registration for online events.</p></div></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Need advanced ecommerce integration? Go with Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Our free Event Tickets plugin lets you power ticket sales with PayPal or Easy Digital Downloads. When you upgrade to Plus, you also have full WooCommerce integration to use additional payment gateways like Stripe or Braintree.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Want access to premium support? Go with Event Tickets Plus.</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Your Events Tickets Plus subscription includes access to</span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/support/\"> <span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">hands-on support</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. Our team is here to help you every step of the way and answer questions as you go, so youll never have to struggle alone if you get stumped.</span></p>\n<p><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Still not sure which plugin is right for you? Learn more about </span></i><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-event-tickets/\"><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Event Tickets and Event Tickets Plus</span></i></a><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">.</span></i></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/news/do-i-need-event-tickets-or-event-tickets-plus/\">Do I Need Event Tickets or Event Tickets Plus?</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:23:\"Community Tickets 4.7.6\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:86:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/community-tickets/community-tickets-4-7-6/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 16 Oct 2020 20:29:15 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:17:\"Community Tickets\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2208648\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:611:\"<p>Summary Maintenance Release This release includes a couple of minor fixes that improve stability and our integration with WooCommerce.  Installation We expect smooth sailing when updating since this is a minor update. That said, it&#8217;s always a good idea to backup your site and test in a development environment as you would with any&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/community-tickets/community-tickets-4-7-6/\">Community Tickets 4.7.6</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Geoff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1985:\"\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Maintenance Release</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">This release includes a couple of minor fixes that improve stability and our integration with WooCommerce.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f4e5.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Installation</h4>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p>We expect smooth sailing when updating since this is a minor update. That said, it&#8217;s always a good idea to backup your site and test in a development environment as you would with any WordPress update.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/2705.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Fixed</h4>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">The following was fixed in this release:</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>We&#8217;re now respecting the existing sale pricing for regular WooCommerce products instead of overriding them.</li><li>There&#8217;s now a unique filter name when filtering the order status changes used for payouts, which helps prevent accidental conflicts.</li></ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/community-tickets/community-tickets-4-7-6/\">Community Tickets 4.7.6</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:57:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:19:\"Event Tickets 5.0.2\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets/event-tickets-5-0-2/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 16 Oct 2020 20:01:35 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Event Tickets\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2208624\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:574:\"<p>Summary Maintenance Release This release focuses on a minor tweaks and fixes. We expect smooth sailing when updating since this is a minor update. That said, it&#8217;s always a good idea to backup your site and test in a development environment as you would with any WordPress update.  Fixed We fixed a few things&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets/event-tickets-5-0-2/\">Event Tickets 5.0.2</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Geoff\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2837:\"\n<p></p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-normal-font-size\">Maintenance Release</p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">This release focuses on a minor tweaks and fixes.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>We expect smooth sailing when updating since this is a minor update. That said, it&#8217;s always a good idea to backup your site and test in a development environment as you would with any WordPress update.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/2705.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Fixed</h4>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">We fixed a few things that are worth calling out.</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>The path to override the <code>blocks/attendees/view-link.php</code> template was corrected in the template&#8217;s documentation.</li><li>Same thing with the <code>/blocks/attendees/title.php</code> and <code>/tickets/view-link.php</code> templates.</li><li>We&#8217;re now correctly respecting required attendee registration fields when they are added to the ticket form.</li></ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.33%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/2728.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Updated</h4>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">We updated the welcome screen in the WordPress admin that a user is taken to when activating the plugin has been refreshed to make it easier to find add-ons, extensions, and support guides for the plugin.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:33.3%\">\n<h4><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/12.0.0-1/72x72/1f5e3.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> Translations</h4>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:66.66%\">\n<p class=\"has-medium-font-size\">Updated language files and strings.</p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>42 new strings added</li><li>25 strings updated</li><li>1 string fuzzied</li><li>28 strings obsoleted</li></ul>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n\n\n<p></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-notes/event-tickets/event-tickets-5-0-2/\">Event Tickets 5.0.2</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n		\n\n					\n										\n					\n		\n		\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"How to Add a Calendar to Any Website\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:72:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-add-a-calendar-to-any-website/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 14 Oct 2020 14:44:40 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"Blog\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Tips & Tricks\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:4:\"blog\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=2207889\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:596:\"<p>If you use The Events Calendar plugins on WordPress, you already know that our tools have you covered for all your event management needs. From creating a flexible calendar to selling tickets and promoting virtual events (plus everything in between), weve got a WordPress plugin for you. But if youre moving your site to a&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-add-a-calendar-to-any-website/\">How to Add a Calendar to Any Website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Lauren\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12180:\"<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you use The Events Calendar plugins on WordPress, you already know that our tools have you covered for all your event management needs. From </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-events-calendar/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">creating a flexible calendar</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> to </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-event-tickets/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">selling tickets</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/promoter/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">promoting</span></a> <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/products/wordpress-virtual-events/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">virtual events</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> (plus everything in between), weve got a WordPress plugin for you.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But if youre moving your site to a different website builder or content management system (CMS), like Squarespace or Wix, you might be searching for a calendar solution that works beyond WordPress. Luckily, weve got one, and its called </span><a href=\"https://loxi.io/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Loxi</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">: The events calendar that works on any website.</span></p>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2207903\" style=\"width: 1488px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2207903\" class=\"wp-image-2207903 size-full\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1478\" height=\"1096\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga.png 1478w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-300x222.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-665x493.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-115x85.png 115w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-768x570.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-430x319.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-645x478.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-1068x792.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-460x341.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-1074x796.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-512x380.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-707x524.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-600x445.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-desktop-mobile-yoga-500x371.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1478px) 100vw, 1478px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2207903\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Loxi works seamlessly on mobile or desktop devices.</p></div></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What is Loxi?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Loxi is an online calendar that you can use on </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">any </span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">website, whether you run your site on Squarespace, Wix, Weebly, WordPress, or somewhere else. We created Loxi specifically for people who want a beautiful, easy-to-manage calendar they can embed anywhere.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You dont even need to have a website to use Loxi. It works as a standalone calendar, too: Use your unique Loxi link anytime you want to send people directly to your calendar. (This works great for linking to your events from Instagram, for example.)</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How Loxi works</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">It only takes a few minutes to build your perfect calendar. Simply create an account and start adding events!</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">But Loxi isnt just a calendar. It also handles event registration and comes with other </span><a href=\"https://loxi.io/features/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">powerful features</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Embed your calendar anywhere. </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">All you do is copy and paste a snippet of code, and voila: your calendar, wherever you want it on your site. No coding skills required.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2207905\" style=\"width: 1186px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2207905\" class=\"size-full wp-image-2207905\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1176\" height=\"480\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share.png 1176w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-300x122.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-665x271.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-140x57.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-768x313.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-430x176.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-645x263.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-1068x436.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-460x188.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-1074x438.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-512x209.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-707x289.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-600x245.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-embed-or-share-500x204.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1176px) 100vw, 1176px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2207905\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Easily embed your calendar or share a link directly to your events on Loxi.</p></div></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Gather RSVPs. </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Loxi lets you gather RSVPs from attendees so you can plan ahead and send email reminders as events draw closer.</span></li>\n<li><b>Recurring events.</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Save time creating events by making a recurring event for your events that happen weekly or monthly.</span></li>\n<li><b>Import events. </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Automatically pull in events from Google, Outlook, and iCalendar.</span></li>\n<li><b>Sleek, mobile-friendly design.</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Loxi is a beautiful, minimalist calendar that was designed to blend in with any website.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2207906\" style=\"width: 1948px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2207906\" class=\"size-full wp-image-2207906\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1938\" height=\"1166\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar.png 1938w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-300x180.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-665x400.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-140x85.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-768x462.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-1536x924.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-430x259.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-645x388.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-1068x643.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-460x277.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-1602x964.png 1602w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-1074x646.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-512x308.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-1611x969.png 1611w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-1832x1102.png 1832w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-707x425.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-600x361.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-love-your-calendar-500x301.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1938px) 100vw, 1938px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2207906\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Customize your calendar to match your site&#8217;s look and feel.</p></div></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Virtual event support. </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Easily identify events as virtual events and embed video and livestreams in your listings.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<p><div id=\"attachment_2207904\" style=\"width: 1610px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-2207904\" class=\"size-full wp-image-2207904\" src=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1600\" height=\"936\" srcset=\"https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings.png 1600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-300x176.png 300w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-665x389.png 665w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-140x82.png 140w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-768x449.png 768w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-1536x899.png 1536w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-430x252.png 430w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-645x377.png 645w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-1068x625.png 1068w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-460x269.png 460w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-1074x628.png 1074w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-512x300.png 512w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-707x414.png 707w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-600x351.png 600w, https://s3.theeventscalendar.com/uploads/2020/10/loxi-dynamic-settings-500x293.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px\" /><p id=\"caption-attachment-2207904\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Use dynamic event settings to show virtual events, and let attendees know when events are canceled or postponed.</p></div></p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Search and filters. </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Users can find and filter events by keyword, location, or category.</span></li>\n<li><b>Unlimited events.</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> Publish as many events as you wanttheres no cap on how much you can publish.</span></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Get started with Loxi for free</span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://loxi.io/signup/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">New users can take Loxi for a spin free for 30 days</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. We dont even ask for a credit card, so you wont see any surprise charges when your trial ends.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you enjoy Loxi, you can subscribe on a flexible monthly plan after your trial ends; cancel anytime.</span></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/blog/how-to-add-a-calendar-to-any-website/\">How to Add a Calendar to Any Website</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:35:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"\n	hourly	\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"u